<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Pollution in cities is the number one killer of young children because of respiratory diseases. Cities are growing at an alarming rate. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I've seen a lot of studies on infant mortality, and respiratory diseases only make the list in vastly underdeveloped countries, who could actually use a hospital or two, not a death sentence.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Worldwide, 800 million people are malnourished, and the number could grow significantly. Farming lands are suffering from soil erosion and desertification. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, famine occurs where there's ineffective government and incentive to regulate (to an extreme) the distribution of food (see Rwanda, North Korea, Angola, et al). There's plenty of food -- it's just getting it to the people that need it that's messy.<br>
<br>
I could go through the rest one-by-one as well, but instead, here's a hint. Find out who's behind overpopulation.org, and you'll have a lot clearer sense of why that site exists.<br>
