<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.celestialrising.com">Celestial Rising</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->,<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.xevserver.com">Xev</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thunderweb>Thunderweb</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#330000>(9/22/03 12:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: World's Human Population</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now you give yours<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The problem is that we don't know what the problem is.<br>
<br>
We come up with these grandiose sweeping headlines pronouncing this the warmest year/decade/century on record, but our record, as far as we can accurately tell, only goes back 100 years or so. Before then, we as a world society didn't have sufficient technology to measure what our earth was like. As a result, the only thing we can look at are tree rings, fossils, dirt deposits, footprints, and the like, which are more anecdotal than scientific, and don't really answer the questions. <br>
<br>
Any reasonable scientific organization can publish the numbers, and by those numbers, our earth is changing. But, we have no idea why. Is it because the changes we're making are multiplying enough to have an actual effect on global climate, or is this just a natural progression out of the last ice age? Everybody's got opinions, but nobody knows for sure, and it's a shame that the loudest and shrillest screeching for changes are coming from organizations with vested financial and political interests in those changes (you'll note that the articles from National Geographic, EPA, and other sources are fact listings -- they don't advocate any particular position, since they're aware of the above few sentences). <br>
<br>
So, my ideas?<br>
<br>
1. Clearly, gather data. Gather meaningful data to try to isolate potential causes, which means detailed measurements and observations of a wide spectrum of data, not just the stuff that makes good headlines (sea levels, temperatures, etc.). <br>
<br>
2. Try to convince developing nations that establishing and building civilization in their countries is in their own best interests, and that a stable nation politically, financially, and socially, is the best course for the people these leaders represent. <br>
<br>
3. Don't take half-assed measures, especially to placate small but loud groups of people who may have different agendas from what they promote. Be sure you have a reasonable idea of what problem you're solving before you start, as well as understand what other problems you may be creating in the process. Measure twice, cut once.<br>
<br>
Well, that's a start, anyway. <br>
<br>
So the killing 2 billion people was a red herring, then?  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=408510">Aeani Thunderweb</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
