<br>
The point of that part of my response was that there's conflicting information about the effects of any of this. There's one school of thought that suggests that global warming would permanently shift the prevailing westerlies north a few degrees of latitude, shifting the meridional jet with it, which would have the effect of heating up the southern US, Northern Africa, and the Middle East and Asian subcontinent, while slightly cooling and bringing more moisture to continental Europe and the UK, much of Russia, and southern Canada. Another group looked at the same change and predicted the addition of liquid moisture at higher latitudes would strength the mean polar wind belts, forcing the midlatitudes further south (having the opposite effect). We really don't know which is right (or if maybe both are wrong). It's hard to justify a course of action without having a decent idea of what it'll do or if it will hurt or help whatever problem we're trying to fix, or if that problem even really exists. At this point, we're still really flying blind. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=408510">Aeani Thunderweb</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
